<h3><span class="oi oi-heart"></span> My Passion for Software Development</h3>
<p>Code was one of my true "first loves" in school, life, and career. My introduction to monolithic, functional programming was on a ridiculously expensive Apple IIe and then a sadly much cheaper Texas Instruments TI-99/4A (oddly <a target="_blank" href="https://wilwheaton.net/2015/09/hello-world/">Wil Wheaton's favorite</a> also). College brought modular, procedural programming on PCs in Turbo Pascal and C, which I leveraged at work for tool and utility programming.</p>
<p>I programmed professionally in C/C++, Turbo Pascal, 3rd party GUI DLL on SCO Linux, and Assembly language on a clustered pair of Burroughs B6x00/7x00 mainframes. Each of those had a PC emulator that replaced their vintage terminal, punch card reader, and 14-inch Winchester disks. </p>

<h3><span class="oi oi-code"></span> My "Return to the Matrix"</h3>
<p>They say if you do what you love, you'll never work a day in your life. And I've always loved working on software. So, when my wife (my other love, back then in school and now) recently resigned her position as Admissions Manager for some well-deserved time off, I also stepped out of my role as Director of IT (Infrastructure & Operations) also, and join her for a "Back to School" career break/sabbatical and some travel.</p>
<p>I wanted to boost my web, Agile, and object-oriented skills. So, I downloaded Visual Studio Code, and hit the Web! I soon learned about <a target="_blank" href="https://codelouisville.org">Code Louisville</a> and decided to take some of their Pluralsight video-based, mentor-facilitated classes on the following:</p>
