<h3><span class="oi oi-person"></span> My Early Years</h3>
<p>I've lived in Kentucky for 20 years now, but was born and raised in Texas. Ended up in Spain, where I learned to program in my High School's first programming class. </p>
<p>I was habitually in the computer lab or debugging code printouts, even on camping trips with my future wife. I planned to go to college and get a Computer Science degree, but the government took away the scholarship they had promised my veteran father his kids would receive.</p>

<h3><span class="oi oi-headphones"></span> My Enlisted Days</h3>
<p>So, unlike my dad, who enlisted in the Army at 13, I decided to join the Air Force at 18 and "see the world" like my pilot uncle did. Then the recruiters rooked me into taking the foreign language test instead, and before long I was in basic training (boot camp) when I received my acceptance letter to the University of New Hampshire. Irony. But soon I would be able say "Здравствуй, Mир" as well as "Hola, Mundo!"</p>

<h3><span class="oi oi-dollar"></span> My "Night School" (and Weekends)</h3>
<p>Over the next 6 years I took Gen Ed and C/Unix programming classes as a computer science major. Luckily, we used computers and databases as linguists, so I found many programming projects and eventually part-time and full-time system administrator duties.</p>

<h3><span class="oi oi-tags"></span> My Officer Days</h3> 
<p>After completing my Bachelor's in Europe and Master's degree in the Pacific, I traded in my Master Sergeant stripes for a "gold bar" with a commission to become a software developer for the next 5 years. I loved coding, and promotions steered me into SDLC management positions (Lead Programmer, Configuration Manager, Software PM) before moving to University of Kentucky to teach ROTC cadets.</p>

<h3><span class="oi oi-cog"></span> My Path in "Higher Ed"</h3>
<p>I had offers for a department head position at Commonwealth Office of Technology in Frankfort and a configuration manager position at Amazon, but decided on a college IT Operations position managing Linux and Windows servers, applications, websites, databases, email, and eventually the entire network.</p>
<p>I was recruited from there to Galen College of Nursing, where I continuously improved Operations and led, mentored, and grew the team from 6 to 17, while building out networks and IT on 8 new campuses. And that's essentially me, in a nutshell!</p>

